      <reaction metaid="metaid_796" id="reaction_9823290" name="SERPINC1 binds heparan sulfate" reversible="false" fast="false" compartment="compartment_984">
        <notes>
          <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Antithrombin III, encoded by the SERPINC1 gene, is a serine protease inhibitor in plasma that inactivates thrombin and other proteases involved in blood clotting (e.g. factor Xa) resulting in an overall decrease in clotting ability (Holmer et al., 1986; Eriksson et al., 1995; van Boven and Lane 1997; Mushunje et al., 2003). Antithrombin III (SERPINC1) binds to membrane-associated glycosaminoglycans such as heparan sulfate on the surface of normal endothelial cells. This binding significantly increases the affinity of antithrombin III (SERPINC1) for thrombin (Holmer et al., 1986; Eriksson et al., 1995; Mushunje et al., 2003; Izaguirre et al., 2007, 2014; Van Walderveen et al., 2010; Atkinson et al., 2024; Olson et al., 2010).</p>
        </notes>
        <annotation>
