      <reaction metaid="metaid_975" id="reaction_8867098" name="Glycophorins bind plasmodium falciparum Ags" reversible="false" fast="false" compartment="compartment_876">
        <notes>
          <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Red blood cell (RBC) glycophorins are integral membrane proteins that are rich in sialic acids. They carry blood group antigenic determinants and serve as ligands for viruses, bacteria, and parasites. They are used as markers to study normal and pathological differentiation of erythroid tissue. RBC glycophorins include glycophorins A (GPYA) to E and are divided into two groups. GPYA and GPYB carry MN and Ss blood group antigens and may act as receptors for Plasmodium falciparum (Cartron and Rahuel 1992). GPYA and GPYB are recognized by P. falciparum erythrocyte-binding antigen 175 (EBA-175) (Wanaguru et al. 2013) and erythrocyte-binding ligand 1 (EBL-1) (Mayer et al. 2009), respectively. GLYC codes for the Gerbich (Ge) blood group antigens and is a receptor for P. falciparum invasion, recognizing EBA-140 on the surface of merozoites (Maier et al. 2003).</p>
        </notes>
        <annotation>
          <rdf:RDF xmlns:rdf="http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/" xmlns:vCard="http://www.w3.org/2001/vcard-rdf/3.0#" xmlns:dcterms="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xmlns:bqbiol="http://biomodels.net/biology-qualifiers/">
