      <reaction metaid="metaid_1003" id="reaction_9769742" name="SMPD1 converts sphingomyelin to ceramide" reversible="false" fast="false" compartment="compartment_876">
        <notes>
          <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Sphingomyelin (SPHM), a phospholipid located in the outer leaflet of the plasma membrane, encrypts tissue factor (TF) procoagulant activity on the surface of TF-bearing resting cells (Wang J et al., 2017; 2019; 2023). The enzymatic activity of sphingomyelin phosphodiesterase (SMPD1, also known as acid sphingomyelinase (ASM)), hydrolyzes SPHM, thereby removing its inhibitory effect on TF (Wang J et al., 2017, 2023; reviewed by Ansari et al., 2019). Experimental evidence has shown that treatment with SMPD1 (ASM) inhibitors reduces lipopolysaccharide (LPS)-induced TF procoagulant activity and thrombin generation in wild-type (C57BL/6J) mice (Wang J et al., 2019).This Reactome event shows SMPD1(ASM)-mediated hydrolysis of SPHM within the TF:SPHM complex forming two products, ceramide and phosphocholine, and releasing &quot;decrypted&quot; TF.</p>
        </notes>
        <annotation>
          <rdf:RDF xmlns:rdf="http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/" xmlns:vCard="http://www.w3.org/2001/vcard-rdf/3.0#" xmlns:dcterms="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xmlns:bqbiol="http://biomodels.net/biology-qualifiers/">
